# Git Workflow

PR-based simplified Git Flow. See also `.claude/CLAUDE.md`.

## Branch model

| Branch | Role |
|--------|------|
| `master` | Production-ready. Protected. Never commit here directly. |
| `feature/` | New functionality (default) |
| `fix/` | Bug fixes |
| `chore/` | Tooling, deps, config |
| `hotfix/` | Urgent production fixes (same PR flow as `fix/`) |

Examples: `feature/income-tracking`, `fix/overview-crash`, `chore/update-deps`

## Golden rules (never violate)

1. **All work stays on the feature/fix/chore/hotfix branch** until the user confirms merge. Never switch to `master` to commit, fix, or "finish" work.
2. **Never commit directly to `master`.**
3. **Never merge into `master` locally.** Integration is always through a GitHub pull request merged with **Create a merge commit**.
4. **Never fast-forward, squash, or rebase-merge** feature branches into `master`.
5. **Never `git branch -D`** on completed work. Use `-d` only after the PR merge. `-D` is for abandoned branches only.
6. **Never rebase or amend commits that are already on `master`.** Amend only on the open branch, before the PR is merged.

## Auto-create branches

When starting **new feature work**, **bug fixes**, or **chore tasks**:

1. `git fetch origin`
2. Check the current branch (`git branch --show-current`).
3. If on `master`, create and switch to a prefixed branch from up-to-date `master`:
   - `git checkout master && git pull origin master`
   - `git checkout -b feature/<short-kebab-description>` (or `fix/`, `chore/`, `hotfix/`)
4. Push the branch early: `git push -u origin HEAD`

## Commits

Create commits automatically as work completes — do not wait for the user to ask.

**Commit discipline:**

- One logical change per commit; keep commits focused and reviewable.
- Use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/): `feat:`, `fix:`, `chore:`, `refactor:`, `docs:`.
- Write professional messages: imperative mood, concise subject (≤ 72 chars), optional body explaining *why* when non-obvious.
- Stage only files relevant to that change — never bundle unrelated work.
- Never commit `.env.local`, credentials, or secrets.
- **No AI attribution** — commits must look human-authored only. Never add `Co-authored-by`, `Made-with: Cursor`, `Made with Cursor`, `Signed-off-by`, or any trailer referencing Cursor, Claude, Copilot, or other AI tools.
- **Agent commits must use a message file**, not `-m`, so Cursor cannot inject `--trailer "Co-authored-by: Cursor …"` into the shell command: write the subject to a temp file, then `git commit -F <msg-file>`.
- **After every `git commit`**, verify the message is clean: `powershell -File scripts/git/verify-last-commit.ps1` (or `git cat-file -p HEAD`). If a trailer slipped through, amend with `git commit --amend -F <msg-file> --no-verify`.
- **Before first commit on a machine**, run `powershell -File scripts/git/install-hooks.ps1` so `prepare-commit-msg` / `commit-msg` hooks strip or block attribution automatically.
- Use `--no-verify` only for attribution cleanup amends, not to bypass other checks.

## Merge gate (user confirmation required)

- **Never** open a PR, merge a PR, or push to `master` unless the user explicitly requests it.
- **Never** force-push to `master`.
- **Never** skip hooks (`--no-verify`) unless the user explicitly asks.

When the user confirms a feature is done, run the **full PR merge flow** below — do not shortcut.

## PR merge flow (run when user confirms merge)

Execute every step in order. Do not skip steps.

### 1. Verify branch is ready

```bash
git branch --show-current          # must be the feature/fix/chore branch
git status                         # working tree clean
git log origin/master..HEAD --oneline
```

If not on the branch, `git checkout <branch>`. If uncommitted changes exist, commit them on the branch first.

### 2. Push the branch

```bash
git push -u origin HEAD
```

### 3. Open a pull request into `master`

```bash
gh pr create --base master --head <branch> \
  --title "<conventional commit subject>" \
  --body "$(cat <<'EOF'
## Summary
<1-3 bullets describing what changed and why>

## Test plan
- [ ] <how to verify>
EOF
)"
```

If `gh` is unavailable, push the branch and give the user the GitHub compare URL:
`https://github.com/lucasrucu/Financial-Dashboard/compare/master...<branch>?expand=1`

### 4. Wait for user review

Present the PR URL. Do **not** merge until the user explicitly says to merge.

### 5. Merge the PR with a merge commit

```bash
gh pr merge <number> --merge --delete-branch
```

**Required:** `--merge` (Create a merge commit). Never use `--squash` or `--rebase`.

If merging via GitHub UI, choose **Create a merge commit** and check **Delete branch**.

### 6. Sync local `master` and clean up

```bash
git fetch origin
git checkout master
git pull origin master
git branch -d <branch>               # safe delete; must succeed after PR merge
```

If `-d` refuses, diagnose with `git log master..<branch>` — do **not** use `-D`.

### 7. Verify

```bash
git status -sb                     # master...origin/master, no ahead/behind
git log --oneline --graph -10      # merge commit + branch fork visible
```

Only stop early if a merge conflict, failed checks, or push rejection needs user input.

## GitHub repo settings (one-time, manual)

Configure in GitHub → Settings → Branches → Branch protection for `master`:

- Require a pull request before merging
- Require branches to be up to date before merging
- Allow **merge commits** only; disable squash and rebase as merge methods

## Merge reminder

When a feature is complete, or at the end of a session with unmerged work on a feature branch:

> Work is on `feature/...`. Review the PR and say when you want me to merge into `master`.

## Anti-patterns

| Bad behavior | Why it breaks the graph |
|---|---|
| `git checkout master` then commit new work | Bypasses the branch; branch never merges |
| Local `git merge feature/x` into `master` | Skips PR; often fast-forwards with no merge commit |
| `git merge` without PR | No review trail; graph may not show on GitHub |
| Squash or rebase merge | Collapses or rewrites branch history |
| Rebase/amend after PR merge | Rewrites SHAs; branches look unmerged |
| `git branch -D` when `-d` fails | Force-deletes branch evidence |
